properties.Title: Update: High Water Advisory Alert For Portions Of The Red River
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a High Water Advisory for the Red River at Ste. Agathe, the Red River Floodway Inlet Control Structure, and within the City of Winnipeg due to expected high flows. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.
Expires: 2019-10-25T11:45:00-05:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization, 2019-10-24T11:56:53-05:00, F748EED0-804F-7F23-801B-B3B60A7DE66A
Area: The Red River at Ste. Agathe, the Red River Floodway Inlet Control Structure, and within the City of Winnipeg
properties.Author: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Be prepared for strong winds tonight and Friday. A developing Pacific low pressure system is forecast to cross the central interior overnight. The associated cold front will then sweep across the southern interior on Friday reaching Washington State in the evening. Strong southerly winds will develop ahead of the low tonight and then shift to west or northwest on Friday. Wind gusts up to 70 km/h are expected except gusts to 80 km/h or more are possible for Chilcotin, Cariboo - south including Williams Lake, 100 Mile and Fraser Canyon. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-25T03:20:47-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-24T11:21:47-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.3569338708.2019
Area: Fraser Canyon - north including Lillooet, Fraser Canyon - south including Lytton, South Thompson, Nicola, North Okanagan - including Vernon, Central Okanagan - including Kelowna, South Okanagan - including Penticton, Shuswap, North Thompson, Chilcotin, Cariboo - north including Quesnel, Cariboo - south including Williams Lake, 100 Mile

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong northwesterly winds are expected on Friday. A cold front over the North Coast will move southwards tonight and cross the Inner South Coast early Friday morning. Southerly winds of 30 to 60 km/h ahead of the cold front will shift to west to northwest 40 to 60 km/h behind the system with some gusts reaching 80 km/h over western sections of Metro Vancouver near the Strait of Georgia. Winds are expected to ease early Friday evening. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-25T09:56:43-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-24T17:57:43-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.1116582718.2019
Area: Metro Vancouver - North Shore including West Vancouver and North Vancouver, Metro Vancouver - central including the City of Vancouver Burnaby and New Westminster, Metro Vancouver - northeast including Coquitlam and Maple Ridge, Metro Vancouver - southeast including Surrey and Langley, Metro Vancouver - southwest including Richmond and Delta, Fraser Valley - west including Abbotsford, Fraser Valley - central including Chilliwack, Fraser Valley - east including Hope, Southern Gulf Islands

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain, at times heavy, is expected. A slow moving Pacific frontal system will bring rain at times heavy to the Central Coast today and tonight. Rainfall amounts of 50 to 70 mm can be expected by Friday morning, when the frontal system finally moves out of the region. Along with heavy rain strong westerly wind gusts to 70 km/h can be expected overnight and Friday morning. ### Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-25T03:19:10-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-24T11:20:10-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.0908319158.2019
Area: Central Coast - inland sections
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected. A low pressure centre will move into the central interior tonight bringing precipitation to the B.C. South Peace River region. Rain will begin this evening and change to snow overnight. The highest snowfall amounts are expected near Tumbler Ridge where 15 cm of snow is forecast by Friday evening while Dawson Creek and Chetwynd can expect about 5 cm of snow. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-25T03:19:29-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-24T11:20:29-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.1320245478.2019
Area: B.C. South Peace River
properties.Author: Environment Canada
